The Path to Nuclear Disarmament
NEW YORK – Weapons of mass destruction and disarmament represent one of the most difficult challenges the world currently faces. One of my priorities as Secretary-General of the United Nations is to promote the global common good and find solutions to problems that do not respect borders.
A world without nuclear weapons is a common good of the highest importance.
My interest in this topic is partly based on personal experiences.
My home country, South Korea, has suffered from the devastation of conventional warfare and has been exposed to the threat of nuclear weapons and other weapons of mass destruction.
Yet, such threat scenarios certainly do not exist only in Asia.
Although the use of atomic weapons has long been considered a taboo, disarmament remains merely an aspiration.
Is a taboo that applies only to the use of such weapons sufficient?
When it comes to nuclear weapons, individual states make the most important decisions.
Yet the UN plays a decisive role in this.
We offer a central forum where states can agree on norms that serve their common interests.
We analyze and teach in order to achieve our agreed-upon goals, and we advocate for them.
Most states have decided to do without nuclear weapons and have summarized their commitments under the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
Yet some states view such weapons as a status symbol, and others see them as the ultimate deterrent against a nuclear attack, which mainly explains the estimated 26,000 nuclear weapons still in existence.
Unfortunately, the doctrine of nuclear deterrence is contagious, making non-proliferation more difficult and creating new risks that nuclear weapons may be used.
The world is still concerned about nuclear activities in North Korea and Iran, and there is broad support for efforts to address these concerns through peaceful means.
In addition, there are concerns that a "nuclear renaissance" may be ahead of us, as nuclear energy is being regarded as a clean energy alternative in times of increasing efforts to combat climate change.
The main concern is that this will lead to the production and use of more nuclear material that must be protected against proliferation and terrorist threats.
The obstacles to disarmament are enormous.
Yet the costs and risks of their alternatives never receive the attention they deserve.
Let us think about the enormous opportunity costs of high military budgets.
According to the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute (Stockholm International Peace Research Institute), military expenditures last year rose to over $1.3 trillion.
Ten years ago, the Brookings Institution published a study estimating the total costs of nuclear weapons in the United States alone to be over $5.8 trillion, including future cleanup costs.
That is, by any definition, a huge investment that could have been used for many other productive purposes.
Concerns about the costs of nuclear weapons and the dangers inherent in them have sparked a global idea fire, exploring how new life could be breathed into nuclear disarmament.
We experienced the UN Disarmament Commission under Hans Blix, the New Agenda Coalition, and Norway's Seven Nation Initiative.
Australia and Japan established the International Commission for Nuclear Non-Proliferation and Disarmament.
Civil society groups and nuclear-armed states have also submitted proposals, such as the Hoover Plan, introduced by Henry Kissinger.
I would like to propose my own five-point plan.
First: I call on all members of the Nuclear Weapons Prohibition Treaty, particularly the nuclear-armed states, to fulfill their obligations under the treaty and to initiate negotiations on effective measures leading to nuclear disarmament.
They could agree on a framework agreement for separate, mutually reinforcing instruments.
Or they could negotiate a nuclear weapons convention supported by a strong control system, as has long been proposed by the UN.
I have sent a draft of such a convention, which provides a good starting point, to all UN member states.
The nuclear powers should actively engage with this issue together with other states at the UN Disarmament Conference in Geneva, the world's only multilateral disarmament negotiation forum.
The world would also welcome the resumption of bilateral negotiations between the United States and Russia, with the aim of significantly and verifiably reducing their nuclear arsenals.
Governments should also invest more in control research and development.
The proposal by the United Kingdom to hold a conference of nuclear powers on the topic of control is a concrete step in the right direction.
Secondly: The permanent members of the Security Council should begin discussing security issues in the process of nuclear disarmament.
You could clearly convey to the states that do not possess nuclear weapons that they will not become victims of a nuclear weapon use or the threat thereof.
The Council could also convene a summit on nuclear disarmament.
States that are not members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty should halt their nuclear weapons programs and take on their own disarmament commitments.
Thirdly: Unilateral moratoriums on nuclear tests and the production of fissile materials may only be permitted to a certain extent.
We need new efforts to bring the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty into force, as well as initiatives to ensure that the Disarmament Conference immediately starts negotiations on a treaty on fissile materials without preconditions.
I support the establishment of nuclear-weapon-free zones in Central Asia and Africa and strongly endorse efforts to establish such zones in the Middle East.
Furthermore, I urgently call on all members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty to conclude their security agreements with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and voluntarily adopt the stricter security provisions of the Additional Protocol.
Fourthly: Nuclear powers frequently circulate descriptions of what they do to achieve these goals.
Yet these reports rarely reach the public.
I would like to ask the nuclear powers to send such materials to the UN Secretariat and to contribute to their further dissemination.
The fact that there is no significant estimate of the total number of nuclear weapons confirms the need for greater transparency.
And finally, various supplementary measures are required.
This includes the elimination of other types of weapons of mass destruction, renewed efforts against terrorism involving weapons of mass destruction, a limitation of the production and trade in conventional weapons, and new weapons bans, including for rockets and space weapons.
If there are real, confirmed advances in disarmament, the ability to eliminate the nuclear threat will grow exponentially.
By gradually eliminating the deadliest weapons of the world and their components, we make it more difficult to carry out terrorist attacks using weapons of mass destruction.
These proposals offer a new beginning, not only for disarmament, but also for strengthening our system of international peace and international security.
